defaultAre there any safety issues associated with capturing, transporting and storing carbon dioxide? How could they be overcome? Who should have responsibility for ensuring these activities are safe? default&#xa0;
defaultCapture
default&#xa0;
default39.
default              
defaultCapture plant is standard i
defaultndustrial process technology.  
defaultThere are significant safety management issues but they should be wholly within the capabilities of a competent operator and would be regulated by the HSE in the normal way.
default&#xa0;
defaultTransport
default&#xa0;
default40.
default              
defaultCO
default2
default is inert but heavier than air, 
defaultand in the event of an escape it will tend to settle at ground level and potentially expose people and animals in the area to risk of suffocation.  There are thus safety risks associated with accidental or malicious pipeline ruptures that will need to be a
defaultddressed and managed.  The Energy Institute has produced technical guidance
default 
defaulton how to manage the transport of 
defaultCO
default2
default safely where there is increased population density.
default&#xa0;
default41.
default              
defaultSafety will be the prime responsibility of the asset owner, regulated by the HSE. 
defaultRisks associated with a properly maintained and regulated CO2 pipeline transmission network should be seen in the context of other potentially hazardous operations such as transporting natural gas and ethylene, which are routinely carried out in the UK.
default&#xa0;
defaultS
defaulttorage
default&#xa0;
default42.
default              
defaultStorage facilities for the UK will be offshore, and will carry risks of offshore working as for offshore oil, but these should be manageable by a competent operator.  Studies of reservoir integrity will be an important part of the development o
defaultf sequestration sites, and we would not expect either seepage or sudden release of 
defaultCO
default2
default from properly designed storage reservoirs.  Safety will be regulated by the HSE as for other offshore activities.
