defaultWhat are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation if CCS fdefaultails?default&#xa0;
default54.
default              
defaultIf CCS is not taken forward at sufficient scale, additional measures and/or technologies would need to be implemented if we are to meet the carbon reduction target. 
default&#xa0;
default55.
default              
defaultThe primary alternative technology is probably new nuclear.  Without CCS, 
defaultthere would be a need for a much larger UK nuclear build programme than currently envisaged
default. 
default This is deliverable from an engineering perspective, but would require large amounts of capital and the substantial expansion of UK and global supply chains.  Fro
defaultm a risk perspective it leaves a significant exposure to the costs of nuclear, especially in a market with relatively few approved vendors and fuel sources.
default&#xa0;
default56.
default              
defaultAlternatively, or additionally, a greater capacity of reliable renewable generation would need
default to be developed. 
default 
defaultIn the case of offshore wind, expansion on a scale to replace the potential role of thermal power stations equipped with CCS would probably be unfeasible given the need to manage generation intermittency on such a large scale.
default 
default To suppor
defaultt this, we would need very large scale and potentially long term energy storage and/or interconnection across Europe and potentially beyond.  Such scenarios have been explored in models, but carry substantial development and deployment risks, which again e
defaultmphasise the value in the optionality of CCS.
default&#xa0;
default57.
default              
defaultTime of use tariffs and demand response techniques could be developed to reduce and adjust the timing of energy usage.
default 
default However, given the scale of the deployment of these techniques that would be needed t
defaulto meet the targets, in the absence of CCS and/or nuclear at the right scale, the impact on the electricity and energy system would be profound, and would probably challenge the limits of public acceptance.
default&#xa0;
default58.
default              
defaultAt the moment it is difficult to foresee a po
defaultwer generation sector that does not include fossil fuel generation being available in time to meet climate reduction targets.
default 
default Failing to progress CCS in time could therefore create political pressure to reduce those targets to avoid the risk of supply sho
defaultrtage.
